Oftentimes, we want to limit the width of an element relative to its parent, and at the same time, to make it dynamic. So having a base width or height with the ability to make it extend based on the available space. Let\rquote s say, for example, that we have a button that should have a minimum width, where it shouldn\rquote t go below it. This is where the maximum and minimum properties become handy.\par
\par
\b Min-Width And Max-Width Properties\b0\par
The first thing to discuss is width-related properties. We have min-width and max-width, and each one of them is important and has its use cases.\par
\par
\b Min Width\b0\par
When setting the value of min-width, its benefit lies in preventing the used value for width property from becoming less than the specified value for min-width. Note that the default value for min-width is auto, which resolves to 0.\par
\par
\par
We have a button with a varying text within in. The text might range from one word to multiple. To guarantee that it will have a minimum width even if it has one word only, min-width should be used. The minimum width is 100px so that even if the button has a very short content, like \ldblquote Done\rdblquote  word, or an icon only, it will still be big enough to be noticed.\par
\par
\par
\par
Max Width\par
When setting the value of max-width, its benefit lies in preventing the used value for width property from becoming more than the specified value for max-width. The default value for max-width is none.\par
\par
By using max-width: 100%, the width of the image won\rquote t exceed the width of its parent. In case the image is smaller than its parent, max-width: 100% won\rquote t have an actual effect on the image, because it\rquote s smaller than its parent.\par
\par
\par
when having a list of tags, it\rquote s recommended to constraint a minimum width for a tag so that if its content is short, the look of it won\rquote t be affected.By having that flexibility, the tag will look good no matter how short the content is. But, what will happen in case the content author entered a very long tag name, and the content management system he uses doesn\rquote t have a maximum character\rquote s length for a tag? We can use max-width as well.\par
.c-tag \{\par
  display: inline-block;\par
  min-width: 100px;\par
  max-width: 250px;\par
  overflow: hidden;\par
  white-space: nowrap;\par
  text-overflow: ellipsis;\par
  /*Other styles*/\par
\}\par
By using max-width, the tag width will be constrained to a specific value. However, that\rquote s not enough. The tag name should be truncated.\par
\par
There are different use cases for the minimum and maximum values with buttons since there are multiple variations of a button component\par
Notice that if the width is too small. Without setting a minimum width, the display can get worse in case there was no text for any reason. Setting a minimum width is important in that case\par
\par
Setting Min Width To Zero With Flexbox\par
The default value for min-width is auto, which is computed to zero. \par
\cf2\b\i\fs32 When an element is a flex item, the value of min-width doesn\rquote t compute to zero. \cf0\b0\i0\fs22\par
\par
The minimum size of a flex item is equal to the size of its contents.\par
